In its most basic form, a bipolar transistor can be seen as a current source that depends on voltage. We first illustrate how such a current source can create an amplifier, thereby highlighting the utility and intrigue of bipolar devices.

Consider the voltage-dependent current source shown in Fig. 4.1(a), where $I_{1}$ is proportional to $V_{1}$: $I_{1}=K V_{1}$. Note that $K$ has the dimension of inverse resistance ${ }^{-1}$. For instance, with $K=0.001 \Omega^{-1}$, an input voltage of 1 V results in an output current of 1 mA. Now, let's construct the circuit in Fig. 4.1(b), where a voltage source $V_{\text {in }}$ controls $I_{1}$, and the output current flows through a load resistor $R_{L}$, generating $V_{\text {out }}$. Our goal is to show that this circuit can function as an amplifier, meaning $V_{\text {out }}$ is an amplified version of $V_{\text {in }}$. Given $V_{1}=V_{\text {in }}$ and $V_{\text {out }}=-R_{L} I_{1}$, we derive

$$
\begin{equation*}
V_{\text {out }}=-K R_{L} V_{\text {in }} \tag{4.1}
\end{equation*}
$$

