description:The graph titled "V_{in} and V_{out} graphs" comprises two time-domain waveforms.

1. **Type of Graph and Function:**
- The graph is a time-domain waveform, depicting the input voltage \( V_{in} \) and the output voltage \( V_{out} \) as functions of time \( t \).

2. **Axes Labels and Units:**
- The horizontal axis represents time \( t \), with units implied to be linear.
- The vertical axis represents voltage, with the top waveform labeled \( V_{in} \) and the bottom \( V_{out} \). Voltage units are not specified, but peak values are indicated.

3. **Overall Behavior and Trends:**
- The \( V_{in} \) waveform exhibits a sinusoidal pattern with a peak voltage labeled \( V_{p} \).
- The \( V_{out} \) waveform also shows a sinusoidal pattern, matching the frequency of \( V_{in} \) but with a higher amplitude.
- The output waveform \( V_{out} \) is inverted relative to \( V_{in} \), indicating a 180-degree phase shift.

4. **Key Features and Technical Details:**
- The amplitude of \( V_{out} \) is labeled \( K R_{L} V_{p} \), signifying that the output voltage is an amplified version of the input voltage by the factor \( K R_{L} \).
- The negative sign in the amplification factor \( -K R_{L} \) indicates inversion.

5. **Annotations and Specific Data Points:**
- The peak value of \( V_{in} \) is marked as \( V_{p} \).
- The peak value of \( V_{out} \) is marked as \( K R_{L} V_{p} \), demonstrating the amplification effect.

Overall, the graph demonstrates the concept of amplification with phase inversion, where the output voltage is an amplified and inverted copy of the input voltage.

Figure 4.1 (a) Voltage-dependent current source, (b) simple amplifier.

Notably, if $K R_{L}>1$, the circuit amplifies the input. The negative sign signifies that the output is an "inverted" version of the input [Fig. 4.1(b)]. The amplification factor or "voltage gain" of the circuit, $A_{V}$, is defined as

$$
\begin{align*}
A_{V} & =\frac{V_{\text {out }}}{V_{\text {in }}}  \tag{4.2}\\
& =-K R_{L} \tag{4.3}
\end{align*}
$$

This gain depends on both the characteristics of the controlled current source and the load resistor. Note that $K$ indicates how strongly $V_{1}$ controls $I_{1}$, directly impacting the gain.
