With our comprehension of transistor operation in the forward active region and the derivation of Eqs. (4.23)-(4.25), we can now develop a model that is beneficial for analyzing and designing circuits, akin to the advancements presented in Chapter 2 for the $p n$ junction.

Given that the base-emitter junction is forward-biased in the active mode, we can insert a diode between the base and emitter terminals. Furthermore, since the current drawn from the collector and flowing into the emitter depends solely on the base-emitter voltage, we incorporate a voltage-controlled current source between the collector and the emitter, resulting in the model depicted in Fig. 4.13. As shown in Fig. 4.11, this current remains unaffected by the collector-emitter voltage.
